t\": \"tool_result\", \"tool\": \"bash\", \"is_error\": false, \"result\": {\"status\": \"success\", \"stdout\": \"C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\workflow\\\\instances\\\\context-pack\\\\sessions\\\\a305a802-3931-4be3-81fa-355fb8ed3c2b\\\\agent-run\\\\analyze-context-pack-inputs__1783100070734-87n83z6n.log:capability: context-pack\\nC:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\workflow\\\\instances\\\\context-pack\\\\sessions\\\\a305a802-3931-4be3-81fa-355fb8ed3c2b\\\\agent-run\\\\analyze-context-pack-inputs__1783100070734-87n83z6n.log:capability = 'context-pack'\\nC:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\workflow\\\\instances\\\\context-pack\\\\sessions\\\\a305a802-3931-4be3-81fa-355fb8ed3c2b\\\\agent-run\\\\analyze-context-pack-inputs__1783100070734-87n83z6n.log:{\\\"event\\\": \\\"intermediate_response\\\", \\\"content\\\": \\\"\\\\nLet me check if there are any capability YAML files or definitions that might guide the context-pack generation:\\\\n\\\"}\\nC:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\workflow\\\\instances\\\\context-pack\\\\sessions\\\\a305a802-3931-4be3-81fa-355fb8ed3c2b\\\\agent-run\\\\analyze-context-pack-inputs__1783100070734-87n83z6n.log:{\\\"event\\\": \\\"tool_call\\\", \\\"tool\\\": \\\"bash\\\", \\\"args\\\": {\\\"command\\\": \\\"findstr /s /i \\\\\\\"capability\\\\\\\" C:\\\\\\\\QAx\\\\\\\\002\\\\\\\\*.*\\\"}}\", \"stderr\": \"\"}}\n68: {\"event\": \"intermediate_response\", \"content\": \"\\nLet me check the specific skill that should be used for this task:\\n\"}\n69: {\"event\": \"tool_call\", \"tool\": \"run_skill\", \"args\": {\"skill_name\": \"analyze-context-pack-inputs\"}}\n70: {\"event\": \"tool_result\", \"tool\": \"run_skill\", \"is_error\": false, \"result\": {\"status\": \"error\", \"message\": \"Skill 'analyze-context-pack-inputs' not found. Available skills: aipods-architect, analyze-test-cases, analyzing-impact, assembling-final-package, automation-execution, automation-planning, calibrating-catalog, calibrating-execution, calibrating-updates, checking-production-readiness, consolidating-backlog, create-capability, create-capability-extension, creating-context-pack, creating-diagrams, creating-qe-master-plan, creating-test-master-plan, defining-qe-strategy, defining-test-strategy, delivering-documentation, designing-structure, establishing-architecture-foundation, executing-automation, executing-tests, find-skills, fix-diagnosis-triage, formatting-platform-export, framework-exploration, g-qe-web-explorer, generating-content, generating-e2e-test-cases, generating-test-cases, human-quality-gate, humanize-spec, implementing-code, implementing-user-stories, interviewing-code, managing-defects, managing-quality-gates, performing-acceptance-testing, planning-code-tasks, planning-epics, playlist-agent-guide, refactor-to-agentic, refining-iteratively, reporting-analysis, repository-cloner, researching-adrs, researching-bounded-contexts, researching-bug-fixing, researching-code-design, researching-feature-impl, researching-prd, researching-refactoring, reviewing-code, reviewing-quality, specifying-architecture, validating-code-interview, web-discovery\"}}\n71: {\"event\": \"intermediate_response\", \"content\": \"\\nI see that the skill mentioned in the instructions doesn't exist. However, I can see there's a `creating-context-pack` skill available which seems more appropriate for this task. Let me use that skill instead:\\n\"}\n72: {\"event\": \"tool_call\", \"tool\": \"run_skill\", \"args\": {\"skill_name\": \"creating-context-pack\"}}\n73: {\"event\": \"tool_result\", \"tool\": \"run_skill\", \"is_error\": false, \"result\": {\"status\": \"success\", \"content\": \"\\nHere the necessary information for running:'creating-context-pack' Instructions: '---\\nname: creating-context-pack\\ndescription: >\\n  Creates a complete context pack for an AI Pod project from a proposal document\\n  and capability YAML definitions. Analyzes all capabilities in the delivery scope,\\n  extracts context_pack.required_files and dynamic_files from each capability YAML,\\n  builds a deduplicated file manifest, infers each file's purpose from its name and\\n  consuming capabilities, then generates project-specific content derived from the\\n  proposal. Output is a dynamically-determined set of markdown files in the target\\n  context-pack directory, plus a manifest audit file.\\n  Enforces Zero Invention Policy — all content traces to the proposal or is\\n  marked as assumption. BUILD and REPAIR modes. FIC context discipline.\\nlicense: Proprietary\\nmetadata:\\n  author: aipods-team\\n  version: 1.1.0\\n  category: meta\\n  tags: context-pack, onboarding, meta, automated, agent-native\\n---\\n\\n# Creating Context Pack — Agent-Native Spec\\n\\n## Quick Start\\nGenerate a complete context pack for a project by analyzing its proposal document\\nand the capability YAMLs that will be executed. The **set of files to generate is\\nnot predetermined** — it is dynamically discovered by reading `spec.context_pack.required_files`\\nand `spec.context_pack.dynamic_files` from each capability YAML in scope.\\nOutput is written to the target `context_pack_path` directory, plus a\\n`CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT-{SESSION_ID}.md` audit trail.\\n\\n## Output Architecture\\n\\n**The output file list is NOT fixed.** It is entirely determined at runtime by Step 2\\n(Capability Analysis). The skill reads every in-scope capability YAML, extracts\\nthe filenames declared in `spec.context_pack.required_files` and\\n`spec.context_pack.dynamic_files`, deduplicates them, and generates exactly those files.\\n\\n```\\n{context_pack_path}/\\n├── {file_1_from_manifest}.md        ← Required by capability A, B\\n├── {file_2_from_manifest}.md        ← Required by capability C\\n├── ...                              ← One file per unique entry in manifest\\n├── {dynamic_file_1}.md              ← Dynamic: initialized with empty template\\n├── {dynamic_file_2}.md              ← Dynamic: initialized with empty template\\n└── CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT-{SESSION_ID}.md  ← Manifest + audit trail\\n```\\n\\n**No file is generated unless at least one capability YAML declares it.**\\nIf a capability declares `required_files: [\\\"foo.md\\\", \\\"bar.md\\\"]`, then `foo.md`\\nand `bar.md` are added to the manifest. If no capability references `baz.md`,\\nit is never created — even if other projects have it.\\n\\n## Parameters\\n| Name | Type | Required | Description | Default |\\n|------|------|----------|-------------|---------|\\n| proposal_path | string | Yes | Path to the proposal document (Markdown, PDF, or Word) | - |\\n| context_pack_path | string | Yes | Target directory for context-pack files | ./context-pack |\\n| capabilities_path | string | Yes | Path to the capabilities directory containing capability YAMLs | - |\\n| capability_scope | string | No | Comma-separated list of capability names to include. If empty, all capabilities found are analyzed. | (all) |\\n| reference_context_pack | string | No | Path to an existing context-pack from another project to use as structural reference for the discovered files | - |\\n| failure_feedback | string | No | Feedback from review (triggers REPAIR mode) | - |\\n\\n**If any Required parameter is not defined, ABORT EXECUTION.**\\n\\n## Workflow\\n\\n### Step 1: Initialize\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n# Context Pack Generator Agent\\n# Persona: Senior Technical Writer & Solution Architect\\n# CRITICAL: NON-INTERACTIVE SESSION.\\n# MISSION: Generate project-specific context pack files from proposal + capability analysis.\\n# The file list is DISCOVERED, not predetermined.\\n\\nSESSION_ID = [Extract from EXECUTION METADATA]\\n\\nIF failure_feedback NOT empty:\\n  MODE = REPAIR\\n  AUDIT_FILE = find existing CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT-*.md in context_pack_path\\n  IF not found → write Gap Report → EXIT\\n  Load AUDIT_FILE → PREVIOUS_MANIFEST\\n  Parse failure_feedback → REPAIR_DIRECTIVES [{ file, instruction, reason }]\\nELSE:\\n  MODE = BUILD\\n  mkdir -p context_pack_path\\n\\n  ## EARLY SIGNAL — FIRST action after mkdir (MANDATORY)\\n  WRITE context_pack_path + '/_progress.json':\\n    { \\\"status\\\": \\\"IN_PROGRESS\\\", \\\"started_at\\\": \\\"<ISO timestamp>\\\",\\n      \\\"skill\\\": \\\"creating-context-pack\\\", \\\"session_id\\\": SESSION_ID }\\n\\nSOURCE_LOG = []\\nCHANGE_LOG = []\\n\\n## Zero Invention Policy\\nNot in proposal → status: assumption. Never infer domain knowledge.\\nIndustry-standard recommendations → explicitly marked as assumptions.\\n\\n## Internal Reasoning: ALL in English regardless of output language.\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 2: Analyze Capabilities — Discover Required Files\\n\\nThis is the **core discovery step**. The file manifest is built entirely from\\ncapability YAML analysis — no hardcoded list.\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n## Capability Analysis — Dynamic File Discovery\\n# Scan capabilities_path for all capability_*.yaml files.\\n# If capability_scope is specified, filter to only those capabilities.\\n\\nCAPABILITY_FILES = glob(capabilities_path + '/capability_*.yaml')\\n\\nIF capability_scope is not empty:\\n  SCOPE_LIST = split(capability_scope, ',')\\n  CAPABILITY_FILES = filter(CAPABILITY_FILES, name matches any in SCOPE_LIST)\\n\\nIF CAPABILITY_FILES is empty → ABORT(\\\"No capability YAMLs found in scope\\\")\\n\\n## Extract context_pack.required_files AND dynamic_files from each capability\\nFILE_MANIFEST = {}  # filename → { capabilities: [], type: \\\"required\\\"|\\\"dynamic\\\" }\\n\\nFOR EACH capability_yaml in CAPABILITY_FILES:\\n  Read capability_yaml → parse YAML\\n  capability_name = metadata.name\\n  required_files = spec.context_pack.required_files OR []\\n  dynamic_files  = spec.context_pack.dynamic_files OR []\\n\\n  FOR EACH file in required_files:\\n    IF file NOT IN FILE_MANIFEST:\\n      FILE_MANIFEST[file] = { capabilities: [], type: \\\"required\\\" }\\n    FILE_MANIFEST[file].capabilities.append(capability_name)\\n    # \\\"required\\\" takes precedence — if already dynamic, upgrade to required\\n    IF FILE_MANIFEST[file].type == \\\"dynamic\\\":\\n      FILE_MANIFEST[file].type = \\\"required\\\"\\n\\n  FOR EACH file in dynamic_files:\\n    IF file NOT IN FILE_MANIFEST:\\n      FILE_MANIFEST[file] = { capabilities: [], type: \\\"dynamic\\\" }\\n    FILE_MANIFEST[file].capabilities.append(capability_name)\\n\\n  SOURCE_LOG.append({\\n    source: capability_yaml,\\n    capability: capability_name,\\n    required: required_files,\\n    dynamic: dynamic_files\\n  })\\n\\n## Result: FILE_MANIFEST contains ONLY the files that capabilities actually need\\n## No assumptions about what files \\\"should\\\" exist — purely data-driven.\\n\\nLOG: \\\"Capability analysis complete: {len(CAPABILITY_FILES)} capabilities analyzed\\\"\\nLOG: \\\"File manifest: {len(FILE_MANIFEST)} unique files discovered\\\"\\nLOG: \\\"  Required: {count where type=='required'}\\\"\\nLOG: \\\"  Dynamic:  {count where type=='dynamic'}\\\"\\nFOR EACH file, info in FILE_MANIFEST:\\n  LOG: \\\"  - {file} [{info.type}] ← {', '.join(info.capabilities)}\\\"\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 3: Analyze Proposal — Extract Project Context\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n## Proposal Ingestion\\nRead proposal document at proposal_path.\\nExtract into PROJECT_CONTEXT:\\n\\nPROJECT_CONTEXT = {\\n  project_name: \\\"\\\",\\n  project_type: \\\"\\\",            # greenfield, brownfield, migration, etc.\\n  domain: \\\"\\\",                  # business domain\\n  problem_statement: \\\"\\\",\\n  goal: \\\"\\\",\\n  scope: {\\n    artifacts: [],             # PRDs, epics, stories, code, tests, etc.\\n    capabilities: [],          # capability names from offering\\n    duration: \\\"\\\",\\n    delivery_model: \\\"\\\"\\n  },\\n  technical_context: {\\n    service_type: \\\"\\\",          # microservice, monolith, library, etc.\\n    key_characteristics: [],   # stateless, deterministic, reactive, etc.\\n    known_tech_decisions: [],  # any tech explicitly mentioned in proposal\\n    integrations: [],          # external systems\\n    database_needs: \\\"\\\",        # if mentioned\\n    api_patterns: []           # REST, GraphQL, etc.\\n  },\\n  domain_concepts: {\\n    entities: [],              # domain objects mentioned\\n    operations: [],            # key operations/functions\\n    glossary: []               # domain terms\\n  },\\n  quality_requirements: {\\n    precision_needs: \\\"\\\",       # if applicable\\n    performance_targets: [],\\n    compliance_needs: []\\n  },\\n  constraints: [],             # any constraints mentioned\\n  stakeholder_context: \\\"\\\"      # who consumes the service, who validates\\n}\\n\\n## If reference_context_pack is provided:\\nIF reference_context_pack exists:\\n  FOR EACH file in FILE_MANIFEST:\\n    IF file exists in reference_context_pack:\\n      Read reference_context_pack/file → REFERENCE_TEMPLATES[file]\\n      # Use as structural reference: section organization, depth, tone\\n      # Do NOT copy content — only extract the skeleton/pattern\\n\\nDetect language from proposal → DETECTED_LANGUAGE\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 4: Infer File Purpose and Generate Content\\n\\nFor each file in FILE_MANIFEST, the agent must **infer the file's purpose from\\nits filename and the capabilities that consume it**, then generate appropriate\\nproject-specific content. There is no hardcoded mapping of filename→content.\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n## Dynamic File Generation\\n# For each file in FILE_MANIFEST, generate content using:\\n# 1. The filename itself (semantic — names describe purpose)\\n# 2. Which capabilities require it (context for relevance)\\n# 3. PROJECT_CONTEXT extracted from proposal\\n# 4. REFERENCE_TEMPLATES[file] for structural guidance (if available)\\n\\n## Purpose Inference Strategy\\n# Context-pack filenames are semantic by convention:\\n#   - The filename describes the concern area (e.g., \\\"security\\\" → security standards)\\n#   - The consuming capabilities indicate the audience:\\n#     * product-definition capabilities → product/business context files\\n#     * software-architecture capabilities → architecture/design files\\n#     * code-development capabilities → coding/tooling/infrastructure files\\n#     * quality-engineering capabilities → testing/automation files\\n#   - If a reference template exists for this filename, its structure reveals\\n#     the expected sections and depth\\n\\n## File Generation Rules\\n\\nRULE 1 — Source Fidelity:\\n  Every technical decision must trace to the proposal or be marked as assumption.\\n  \\\"The proposal mentions X\\\" → include as fact.\\n  \\\"Standard practice for this type of service\\\" → include as assumption with rationale.\\n\\nRULE 2 — Appropriate Depth:\\n  Greenfield projects: Include recommended patterns and standards (marked as\\n  assumptions/recommendations) since no existing codebase constrains decisions.\\n  Brownfield projects: Focus on documented constraints and existing patterns.\\n\\nRULE 3 — Cross-File Consistency:\\n  When generating file N, check already-generated files 1..N-1 for consistency.\\n  Tech decisions, tool names, patterns, and domain vocabulary must align.\\n\\nRULE 4 — Domain Vocabulary:\\n  Use domain terms from the proposal consistently across all files.\\n  If a glossary/domain file was generated earlier, it is the canonical source.\\n\\nRULE 5 — No Hallucinated Structure:\\n  If a file is completely unknown (no reference template, no semantic clue from\\n  the filename), generate a minimal file with:\\n    - H1 title derived from filename\\n    - A note: \\\"This file's structure was not determined from reference templates.\\n      Content derived from proposal context. Review and restructure as needed.\\\"\\n    - Best-effort content from PROJECT_CONTEXT relevant to the filename's topic\\n\\n## Generation Order\\n# Sort FILE_MANIFEST to generate foundational files first:\\n#   1. Files consumed by the most capabilities (broadest impact)\\n#   2. Files whose names suggest foundational content (domain, background, constraints)\\n#   3. Files consumed by fewer capabilities (more specialized)\\n#   4. Dynamic files last (initialized with empty templates)\\n#\\n# This ensures later files can reference decisions made in earlier files.\\n\\nGENERATION_ORDER = sort FILE_MANIFEST by:\\n  - type == \\\"dynamic\\\" last\\n  - number of consuming capabilities (descending)\\n  - alphabetical tiebreak\\n\\nFOR EACH file in GENERATION_ORDER:\\n  info = FILE_MANIFEST[file]\\n\\n  ## Infer purpose\\n  PURPOSE = infer_from(\\n    filename = file,\\n    consuming_capabilities = info.capabilities,\\n    reference_template = REFERENCE_TEMPLATES.get(file, None),\\n    project_context = PROJECT_CONTEXT\\n  )\\n\\n  IF info.type == \\\"dynamic\\\":\\n    ## Dynamic files: initialize with empty templates\\n    ## These are session-state files updated by skills during execution\\n    Generate minimal template with:\\n      - H1 title: \\\"{purpose} — {PROJECT_CONTEXT.project_name}\\\"\\n      - Empty table or placeholder indicating \\\"not yet started\\\"\\n      - No project-specific content (populated at runtime by skills)\\n\\n  ELSE:\\n    ## Required files: generate full project-specific content\\n    IF REFERENCE_TEMPLATES[file] exists:\\n      ## Use reference as structural skeleton\\n      Extract section headings and organization from REFERENCE_TEMPLATES[file]\\n      Replace all content with PROJECT_CONTEXT-derived content\\n      Adapt sections to this project's domain (add/remove sections as needed)\\n    ELSE:\\n      ## No reference — infer structure from purpose and consuming capabilities\\n      Generate sections based on:\\n        - The inferred purpose\\n        - What the consuming capabilities would need from this file\\n        - PROJECT_CONTEXT fields relevant to this purpose\\n        - Standard industry structure for this type of document\\n\\n    Apply structural conventions:\\n      - H1 title: \\\"# {Inferred Purpose Title}\\\\n# {project_name} — {project_type}\\\"\\n      - \\\"**Document Version:** 1.0\\\"\\n      - Numbered H2 sections\\n      - Tables for structured data\\n      - Code blocks for configs, commands, directory structures\\n      - Footer: \\\"*{project_name} {purpose} — Globant Delivery Team*\\\"\\n\\n  Write file to context_pack_path/file\\n  CHANGE_LOG.append({ file: file, action: \\\"generated\\\", purpose: PURPOSE,\\n                      consumers: info.capabilities, had_reference: bool })\\n\\nLOG: \\\"Generated {file} [{info.type}] — purpose: {PURPOSE}\\\"\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 5: Quality Validation Gate\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n## Validate dynamically — checks adapt to whatever files were generated\\n\\n1. Completeness:\\n   FOR EACH file in FILE_MANIFEST:\\n     ASSERT file exists at context_pack_path/file AND is non-empty\\n   No file in FILE_MANIFEST may be missing.\\n\\n2. Cross-Consistency (apply ONLY to files that were actually generated):\\n   - IF multiple files discuss technology choices:\\n     Verify same tools, versions, and patterns across all of them\\n   - IF multiple files discuss testing:\\n     Verify same frameworks and thresholds\\n   - IF any file declares a constraint:\\n     Verify no other file contradicts it\\n\\n3. Domain Vocabulary:\\n   Extract domain terms from proposal.\\n   IF a glossary/domain file exists → it is the canonical vocabulary source.\\n   Verify domain terms used consistently across all generated files.\\n\\n4. Source Fidelity:\\n   FOR EACH generated file:\\n     Verify no technical decision is presented as established fact\\n     unless it traces to the proposal.\\n     Greenfield recommendations must be marked as assumptions.\\n\\n5. Dynamic Files (if any in manifest):\\n   Verify they exist with valid empty templates.\\n   Verify they contain NO project-specific decisions (they are runtime-populated).\\n\\nIF corrections needed → apply in place, log to CHANGE_LOG\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 6: Write Audit Trail\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n1. Write CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT-{SESSION_ID}.md containing:\\n\\n   ## Session Metadata\\n   - session_id, version, mode (BUILD/REPAIR), timestamp, detected_language\\n\\n   ## Capability Analysis\\n   FOR EACH capability in SOURCE_LOG:\\n     - capability_name, yaml_path, required_files[], dynamic_files[]\\n\\n   ## File Manifest (the core traceability artifact)\\n   Table: | Filename | Type | Consuming Capabilities | Had Reference | Purpose Inferred |\\n   FOR EACH file in FILE_MANIFEST:\\n     One row per file\\n\\n   ## Proposal Sections Referenced\\n   Which parts of the proposal were used to populate each file\\n\\n   ## Assumptions Made\\n   Consolidated list of all items marked as assumption across all files\\n   Each with: file, section, assumption text, rationale\\n\\n   ## Decisions Made (CHANGE_LOG)\\n   All generation decisions, corrections, and cross-consistency fixes\\n\\n   ## Cross-Consistency Check Results\\n   Summary of validation gate outcomes\\n\\n   ## Summary\\n   - Capabilities analyzed: N\\n   - Unique files discovered: M\\n   - Required files generated: X\\n   - Dynamic files initialized: Y\\n   - Assumptions count: Z\\n\\n2. Update _progress.json:\\n   { \\\"status\\\": \\\"COMPLETE\\\", \\\"completed_at\\\": \\\"<ISO timestamp>\\\",\\n     \\\"total\\\": len(FILE_MANIFEST), \\\"completed\\\": len(FILE_MANIFEST),\\n     \\\"items\\\": [{ \\\"name\\\": file, \\\"status\\\": \\\"COMPLETE\\\" } for each file] }\\n\\n3. Verify all files exist and are non-empty\\n\\n4. LOG: \\\"Context pack complete: {N} files generated for {M} capabilities\\\"\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n## Structural Conventions for Generated Files\\n\\nWhen generating any context-pack file, apply these structural conventions regardless\\nof what file it is:\\n\\n- **H1 title:** `# {Inferred Purpose}\\\\n# {Project Name} — {Project Type}`\\n- **Version header:** `**Document Version:** 1.0`\\n- **Numbered H2 sections** with domain-specific content\\n- **Tables** for structured data (tools, environments, dependencies, mappings)\\n- **Code blocks** for configuration examples, directory structures, shell commands\\n- **Footer:** `*{Project Name} {Inferred Purpose} — Globant Delivery Team*`\\n\\nWhen a `reference_context_pack` is provided and contains a matching filename,\\nuse its section structure as a skeleton — but replace ALL content with\\nproject-specific material derived from the proposal.\\n\\n## Common Rationalizations\\n\\n| Excuse | Why It Fails | Counter |\\n|--------|-------------|---------|\\n| \\\"The proposal doesn't mention tech stack, I'll pick what I know\\\" | Ungrounded tech decisions constrain the architecture phase unnecessarily | Mark recommendations as assumptions. Let the ADR phase make binding decisions. |\\n| \\\"This is greenfield, so I'll be vague\\\" | Vague context packs produce vague PRDs, vague epics, and vague code | Be specific with recommendations, but mark them as assumptions. Specificity enables the architecture phase to accept or override. |\\n| \\\"I'll just copy the reference template and change the project name\\\" | Copy-paste context packs contain irrelevant constraints from other projects | Extract structure from the reference, but generate content from THIS proposal. Every fact must trace to this project's proposal. |\\n| \\\"I don't know what this file is for, I'll skip it\\\" | A capability declared it as required — it will fail if the file is missing | Infer purpose from filename + consuming capabilities. Generate best-effort content. Flag uncertainty in the audit trail. |\\n| \\\"The proposal doesn't discuss security, I'll skip security.md\\\" | The capability declared it required — absence of discussion ≠ absence of need | Generate standard practices marked as assumptions. Flag in the audit that the proposal did not address this topic. |\\n\\n## Red Flags\\n\\nSigns that this context pack is being generated superficially:\\n\\n- All files contain identical boilerplate with only the project name changed\\n- Domain-specific concerns from the proposal don't appear in any generated file\\n- Files that discuss technology mention different/inconsistent tool sets\\n- No assumptions are marked — indicates either a perfect proposal (unlikely) or insufficient scrutiny\\n- Files were generated that no capability requires (phantom files)\\n- Files that a capability requires were NOT generated (missing files)\\n- Dynamic files contain project-specific decisions (they should be empty templates)\\n\\n## Verification Checklist\\n\\nEvery item requires **evidence**, not assertion:\\n\\n- [ ] FILE_MANIFEST matches capability YAMLs exactly — Evidence: audit trail manifest vs capability YAML cross-check\\n- [ ] Every file in FILE_MANIFEST was generated — Evidence: file existence check\\n- [ ] No file was generated outside FILE_MANIFEST — Evidence: directory listing vs manifest comparison\\n- [ ] Domain vocabulary consistent across files — Evidence: grep domain terms across all files\\n- [ ] Tech decisions aligned across related files — Evidence: tool/version cross-reference\\n- [ ] Greenfield recommendations marked as assumptions — Evidence: \\\"assumption\\\" or \\\"recommended\\\" markers present\\n- [ ] Dynamic files initialized with empty templates only — Evidence: no project decisions in dynamic files\\n- [ ] Audit trail captures all decisions — Evidence: CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT file present with complete manifest\\n\\n## Reference Files\\n- `references/file-generation-guide.md` — Structural conventions and purpose-inference patterns\\n''; BE AWARE OF THE CORRECT ENVIRONMENT SETTINGS AND CONTEXT: 'native''. USER PLATFORM: 'windows''. Run the scripts following the instructions and return to the user a detailed description of the scripts outputs.\\nAlso you have instructions for building and validating the execution environment for the 'creating-context-pack' skill based on the requirements specified in its content. Your goal is to:\\n\\n## Skill Information\\n\\n**Skill Name:** creating-context-pack\\n**Execution Context:** native\\n**Skill Directory:** C:\\\\Users\\\\claudio.feitosa\\\\.coda\\\\skills\\\\creating-context-pack\\n**Scripts Directory:** C:\\\\Users\\\\claudio.feitosa\\\\.coda\\\\skills\\\\creating-context-pack/scripts/\\n**Artifact Output Directory:** C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\.coda\\\\skill-artifacts\\n**Artifact Environment Variable:** CODA_SKILL_OUTPUT_DIR (already set to C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\.coda\\\\skill-artifacts)\\n**Setup Timeout:** 120 seconds\\n\\n### 📁 Artifact Output Location\\n\\nAll generated files, artifacts, and output from this skill MUST be written to:\\n```\\nC:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\.coda\\\\skill-artifacts\\n```\\n\\nThe environment variable `CODA_SKILL_OUTPUT_DIR` is already set and points to this directory.\\n\\n**IMPORTANT - Output Directory Rules:**\\n- **DO:** Create your project/artifact folders DIRECTLY in `C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\.coda\\\\skill-artifacts`\\n- **DO:** Use the project name as the folder name (e.g., `C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\.coda\\\\skill-artifacts/my-app/`)\\n\\n**Examples:**\\n\\n**CORRECT Structure:**\\n```\\nUse the skill-creator tool for creating a new skill called \\ngithub-review for reviewing github pull requests, the tool...[etc]\\n```\\nThe artifacts generated will be saved in: `C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\.coda\\\\skill-artifacts/github-reviewer/`\\n## Skill Requirements\\n\\n---\\nname: creating-context-pack\\ndescription: >\\n  Creates a complete context pack for an AI Pod project from a proposal document\\n  and capability YAML definitions. Analyzes all capabilities in the delivery scope,\\n  extracts context_pack.required_files and dynamic_files from each capability YAML,\\n  builds a deduplicated file manifest, infers each file's purpose from its name and\\n  consuming capabilities, then generates project-specific content derived from the\\n  proposal. Output is a dynamically-determined set of markdown files in the target\\n  context-pack directory, plus a manifest audit file.\\n  Enforces Zero Invention Policy — all content traces to the proposal or is\\n  marked as assumption. BUILD and REPAIR modes. FIC context discipline.\\nlicense: Proprietary\\nmetadata:\\n  author: aipods-team\\n  version: 1.1.0\\n  category: meta\\n  tags: context-pack, onboarding, meta, automated, agent-native\\n---\\n\\n# Creating Context Pack — Agent-Native Spec\\n\\n## Quick Start\\nGenerate a complete context pack for a project by analyzing its proposal document\\nand the capability YAMLs that will be executed. The **set of files to generate is\\nnot predetermined** — it is dynamically discovered by reading `spec.context_pack.required_files`\\nand `spec.context_pack.dynamic_files` from each capability YAML in scope.\\nOutput is written to the target `context_pack_path` directory, plus a\\n`CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT-{SESSION_ID}.md` audit trail.\\n\\n## Output Architecture\\n\\n**The output file list is NOT fixed.** It is entirely determined at runtime by Step 2\\n(Capability Analysis). The skill reads every in-scope capability YAML, extracts\\nthe filenames declared in `spec.context_pack.required_files` and\\n`spec.context_pack.dynamic_files`, deduplicates them, and generates exactly those files.\\n\\n```\\n{context_pack_path}/\\n├── {file_1_from_manifest}.md        ← Required by capability A, B\\n├── {file_2_from_manifest}.md        ← Required by capability C\\n├── ...                              ← One file per unique entry in manifest\\n├── {dynamic_file_1}.md              ← Dynamic: initialized with empty template\\n├── {dynamic_file_2}.md              ← Dynamic: initialized with empty template\\n└── CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT-{SESSION_ID}.md  ← Manifest + audit trail\\n```\\n\\n**No file is generated unless at least one capability YAML declares it.**\\nIf a capability declares `required_files: [\\\"foo.md\\\", \\\"bar.md\\\"]`, then `foo.md`\\nand `bar.md` are added to the manifest. If no capability references `baz.md`,\\nit is never created — even if other projects have it.\\n\\n## Parameters\\n| Name | Type | Required | Description | Default |\\n|------|------|----------|-------------|---------|\\n| proposal_path | string | Yes | Path to the proposal document (Markdown, PDF, or Word) | - |\\n| context_pack_path | string | Yes | Target directory for context-pack files | ./context-pack |\\n| capabilities_path | string | Yes | Path to the capabilities directory containing capability YAMLs | - |\\n| capability_scope | string | No | Comma-separated list of capability names to include. If empty, all capabilities found are analyzed. | (all) |\\n| reference_context_pack | string | No | Path to an existing context-pack from another project to use as structural reference for the discovered files | - |\\n| failure_feedback | string | No | Feedback from review (triggers REPAIR mode) | - |\\n\\n**If any Required parameter is not defined, ABORT EXECUTION.**\\n\\n## Workflow\\n\\n### Step 1: Initialize\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n# Context Pack Generator Agent\\n# Persona: Senior Technical Writer & Solution Architect\\n# CRITICAL: NON-INTERACTIVE SESSION.\\n# MISSION: Generate project-specific context pack files from proposal + capability analysis.\\n# The file list is DISCOVERED, not predetermined.\\n\\nSESSION_ID = [Extract from EXECUTION METADATA]\\n\\nIF failure_feedback NOT empty:\\n  MODE = REPAIR\\n  AUDIT_FILE = find existing CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT-*.md in context_pack_path\\n  IF not found → write Gap Report → EXIT\\n  Load AUDIT_FILE → PREVIOUS_MANIFEST\\n  Parse failure_feedback → REPAIR_DIRECTIVES [{ file, instruction, reason }]\\nELSE:\\n  MODE = BUILD\\n  mkdir -p context_pack_path\\n\\n  ## EARLY SIGNAL — FIRST action after mkdir (MANDATORY)\\n  WRITE context_pack_path + '/_progress.json':\\n    { \\\"status\\\": \\\"IN_PROGRESS\\\", \\\"started_at\\\": \\\"<ISO timestamp>\\\",\\n      \\\"skill\\\": \\\"creating-context-pack\\\", \\\"session_id\\\": SESSION_ID }\\n\\nSOURCE_LOG = []\\nCHANGE_LOG = []\\n\\n## Zero Invention Policy\\nNot in proposal → status: assumption. Never infer domain knowledge.\\nIndustry-standard recommendations → explicitly marked as assumptions.\\n\\n## Internal Reasoning: ALL in English regardless of output language.\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 2: Analyze Capabilities — Discover Required Files\\n\\nThis is the **core discovery step**. The file manifest is built entirely from\\ncapability YAML analysis — no hardcoded list.\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n## Capability Analysis — Dynamic File Discovery\\n# Scan capabilities_path for all capability_*.yaml files.\\n# If capability_scope is specified, filter to only those capabilities.\\n\\nCAPABILITY_FILES = glob(capabilities_path + '/capability_*.yaml')\\n\\nIF capability_scope is not empty:\\n  SCOPE_LIST = split(capability_scope, ',')\\n  CAPABILITY_FILES = filter(CAPABILITY_FILES, name matches any in SCOPE_LIST)\\n\\nIF CAPABILITY_FILES is empty → ABORT(\\\"No capability YAMLs found in scope\\\")\\n\\n## Extract context_pack.required_files AND dynamic_files from each capability\\nFILE_MANIFEST = {}  # filename → { capabilities: [], type: \\\"required\\\"|\\\"dynamic\\\" }\\n\\nFOR EACH capability_yaml in CAPABILITY_FILES:\\n  Read capability_yaml → parse YAML\\n  capability_name = metadata.name\\n  required_files = spec.context_pack.required_files OR []\\n  dynamic_files  = spec.context_pack.dynamic_files OR []\\n\\n  FOR EACH file in required_files:\\n    IF file NOT IN FILE_MANIFEST:\\n      FILE_MANIFEST[file] = { capabilities: [], type: \\\"required\\\" }\\n    FILE_MANIFEST[file].capabilities.append(capability_name)\\n    # \\\"required\\\" takes precedence — if already dynamic, upgrade to required\\n    IF FILE_MANIFEST[file].type == \\\"dynamic\\\":\\n      FILE_MANIFEST[file].type = \\\"required\\\"\\n\\n  FOR EACH file in dynamic_files:\\n    IF file NOT IN FILE_MANIFEST:\\n      FILE_MANIFEST[file] = { capabilities: [], type: \\\"dynamic\\\" }\\n    FILE_MANIFEST[file].capabilities.append(capability_name)\\n\\n  SOURCE_LOG.append({\\n    source: capability_yaml,\\n    capability: capability_name,\\n    required: required_files,\\n    dynamic: dynamic_files\\n  })\\n\\n## Result: FILE_MANIFEST contains ONLY the files that capabilities actually need\\n## No assumptions about what files \\\"should\\\" exist — purely data-driven.\\n\\nLOG: \\\"Capability analysis complete: {len(CAPABILITY_FILES)} capabilities analyzed\\\"\\nLOG: \\\"File manifest: {len(FILE_MANIFEST)} unique files discovered\\\"\\nLOG: \\\"  Required: {count where type=='required'}\\\"\\nLOG: \\\"  Dynamic:  {count where type=='dynamic'}\\\"\\nFOR EACH file, info in FILE_MANIFEST:\\n  LOG: \\\"  - {file} [{info.type}] ← {', '.join(info.capabilities)}\\\"\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 3: Analyze Proposal — Extract Project Context\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n## Proposal Ingestion\\nRead proposal document at proposal_path.\\nExtract into PROJECT_CONTEXT:\\n\\nPROJECT_CONTEXT = {\\n  project_name: \\\"\\\",\\n  project_type: \\\"\\\",            # greenfield, brownfield, migration, etc.\\n  domain: \\\"\\\",                  # business domain\\n  problem_statement: \\\"\\\",\\n  goal: \\\"\\\",\\n  scope: {\\n    artifacts: [],             # PRDs, epics, stories, code, tests, etc.\\n    capabilities: [],          # capability names from offering\\n    duration: \\\"\\\",\\n    delivery_model: \\\"\\\"\\n  },\\n  technical_context: {\\n    service_type: \\\"\\\",          # microservice, monolith, library, etc.\\n    key_characteristics: [],   # stateless, deterministic, reactive, etc.\\n    known_tech_decisions: [],  # any tech explicitly mentioned in proposal\\n    integrations: [],          # external systems\\n    database_needs: \\\"\\\",        # if mentioned\\n    api_patterns: []           # REST, GraphQL, etc.\\n  },\\n  domain_concepts: {\\n    entities: [],              # domain objects mentioned\\n    operations: [],            # key operations/functions\\n    glossary: []               # domain terms\\n  },\\n  quality_requirements: {\\n    precision_needs: \\\"\\\",       # if applicable\\n    performance_targets: [],\\n    compliance_needs: []\\n  },\\n  constraints: [],             # any constraints mentioned\\n  stakeholder_context: \\\"\\\"      # who consumes the service, who validates\\n}\\n\\n## If reference_context_pack is provided:\\nIF reference_context_pack exists:\\n  FOR EACH file in FILE_MANIFEST:\\n    IF file exists in reference_context_pack:\\n      Read reference_context_pack/file → REFERENCE_TEMPLATES[file]\\n      # Use as structural reference: section organization, depth, tone\\n      # Do NOT copy content — only extract the skeleton/pattern\\n\\nDetect language from proposal → DETECTED_LANGUAGE\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 4: Infer File Purpose and Generate Content\\n\\nFor each file in FILE_MANIFEST, the agent must **infer the file's purpose from\\nits filename and the capabilities that consume it**, then generate appropriate\\nproject-specific content. There is no hardcoded mapping of filename→content.\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n## Dynamic File Generation\\n# For each file in FILE_MANIFEST, generate content using:\\n# 1. The filename itself (semantic — names describe purpose)\\n# 2. Which capabilities require it (context for relevance)\\n# 3. PROJECT_CONTEXT extracted from proposal\\n# 4. REFERENCE_TEMPLATES[file] for structural guidance (if available)\\n\\n## Purpose Inference Strategy\\n# Context-pack filenames are semantic by convention:\\n#   - The filename describes the concern area (e.g., \\\"security\\\" → security standards)\\n#   - The consuming capabilities indicate the audience:\\n#     * product-definition capabilities → product/business context files\\n#     * software-architecture capabilities → architecture/design files\\n#     * code-development capabilities → coding/tooling/infrastructure files\\n#     * quality-engineering capabilities → testing/automation files\\n#   - If a reference template exists for this filename, its structure reveals\\n#     the expected sections and depth\\n\\n## File Generation Rules\\n\\nRULE 1 — Source Fidelity:\\n  Every technical decision must trace to the proposal or be marked as assumption.\\n  \\\"The proposal mentions X\\\" → include as fact.\\n  \\\"Standard practice for this type of service\\\" → include as assumption with rationale.\\n\\nRULE 2 — Appropriate Depth:\\n  Greenfield projects: Include recommended patterns and standards (marked as\\n  assumptions/recommendations) since no existing codebase constrains decisions.\\n  Brownfield projects: Focus on documented constraints and existing patterns.\\n\\nRULE 3 — Cross-File Consistency:\\n  When generating file N, check already-generated files 1..N-1 for consistency.\\n  Tech decisions, tool names, patterns, and domain vocabulary must align.\\n\\nRULE 4 — Domain Vocabulary:\\n  Use domain terms from the proposal consistently across all files.\\n  If a glossary/domain file was generated earlier, it is the canonical source.\\n\\nRULE 5 — No Hallucinated Structure:\\n  If a file is completely unknown (no reference template, no semantic clue from\\n  the filename), generate a minimal file with:\\n    - H1 title derived from filename\\n    - A note: \\\"This file's structure was not determined from reference templates.\\n      Content derived from proposal context. Review and restructure as needed.\\\"\\n    - Best-effort content from PROJECT_CONTEXT relevant to the filename's topic\\n\\n## Generation Order\\n# Sort FILE_MANIFEST to generate foundational files first:\\n#   1. Files consumed by the most capabilities (broadest impact)\\n#   2. Files whose names suggest foundational content (domain, background, constraints)\\n#   3. Files consumed by fewer capabilities (more specialized)\\n#   4. Dynamic files last (initialized with empty templates)\\n#\\n# This ensures later files can reference decisions made in earlier files.\\n\\nGENERATION_ORDER = sort FILE_MANIFEST by:\\n  - type == \\\"dynamic\\\" last\\n  - number of consuming capabilities (descending)\\n  - alphabetical tiebreak\\n\\nFOR EACH file in GENERATION_ORDER:\\n  info = FILE_MANIFEST[file]\\n\\n  ## Infer purpose\\n  PURPOSE = infer_from(\\n    filename = file,\\n    consuming_capabilities = info.capabilities,\\n    reference_template = REFERENCE_TEMPLATES.get(file, None),\\n    project_context = PROJECT_CONTEXT\\n  )\\n\\n  IF info.type == \\\"dynamic\\\":\\n    ## Dynamic files: initialize with empty templates\\n    ## These are session-state files updated by skills during execution\\n    Generate minimal template with:\\n      - H1 title: \\\"{purpose} — {PROJECT_CONTEXT.project_name}\\\"\\n      - Empty table or placeholder indicating \\\"not yet started\\\"\\n      - No project-specific content (populated at runtime by skills)\\n\\n  ELSE:\\n    ## Required files: generate full project-specific content\\n    IF REFERENCE_TEMPLATES[file] exists:\\n      ## Use reference as structural skeleton\\n      Extract section headings and organization from REFERENCE_TEMPLATES[file]\\n      Replace all content with PROJECT_CONTEXT-derived content\\n      Adapt sections to this project's domain (add/remove sections as needed)\\n    ELSE:\\n      ## No reference — infer structure from purpose and consuming capabilities\\n      Generate sections based on:\\n        - The inferred purpose\\n        - What the consuming capabilities would need from this file\\n        - PROJECT_CONTEXT fields relevant to this purpose\\n        - Standard industry structure for this type of document\\n\\n    Apply structural conventions:\\n      - H1 title: \\\"# {Inferred Purpose Title}\\\\n# {project_name} — {project_type}\\\"\\n      - \\\"**Document Version:** 1.0\\\"\\n      - Numbered H2 sections\\n      - Tables for structured data\\n      - Code blocks for configs, commands, directory structures\\n      - Footer: \\\"*{project_name} {purpose} — Globant Delivery Team*\\\"\\n\\n  Write file to context_pack_path/file\\n  CHANGE_LOG.append({ file: file, action: \\\"generated\\\", purpose: PURPOSE,\\n                      consumers: info.capabilities, had_reference: bool })\\n\\nLOG: \\\"Generated {file} [{info.type}] — purpose: {PURPOSE}\\\"\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 5: Quality Validation Gate\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n## Validate dynamically — checks adapt to whatever files were generated\\n\\n1. Completeness:\\n   FOR EACH file in FILE_MANIFEST:\\n     ASSERT file exists at context_pack_path/file AND is non-empty\\n   No file in FILE_MANIFEST may be missing.\\n\\n2. Cross-Consistency (apply ONLY to files that were actually generated):\\n   - IF multiple files discuss technology choices:\\n     Verify same tools, versions, and patterns across all of them\\n   - IF multiple files discuss testing:\\n     Verify same frameworks and thresholds\\n   - IF any file declares a constraint:\\n     Verify no other file contradicts it\\n\\n3. Domain Vocabulary:\\n   Extract domain terms from proposal.\\n   IF a glossary/domain file exists → it is the canonical vocabulary source.\\n   Verify domain terms used consistently across all generated files.\\n\\n4. Source Fidelity:\\n   FOR EACH generated file:\\n     Verify no technical decision is presented as established fact\\n     unless it traces to the proposal.\\n     Greenfield recommendations must be marked as assumptions.\\n\\n5. Dynamic Files (if any in manifest):\\n   Verify they exist with valid empty templates.\\n   Verify they contain NO project-specific decisions (they are runtime-populated).\\n\\nIF corrections needed → apply in place, log to CHANGE_LOG\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n### Step 6: Write Audit Trail\\n\\n**Command:**\\n```\\n1. Write CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT-{SESSION_ID}.md containing:\\n\\n   ## Session Metadata\\n   - session_id, version, mode (BUILD/REPAIR), timestamp, detected_language\\n\\n   ## Capability Analysis\\n   FOR EACH capability in SOURCE_LOG:\\n     - capability_name, yaml_path, required_files[], dynamic_files[]\\n\\n   ## File Manifest (the core traceability artifact)\\n   Table: | Filename | Type | Consuming Capabilities | Had Reference | Purpose Inferred |\\n   FOR EACH file in FILE_MANIFEST:\\n     One row per file\\n\\n   ## Proposal Sections Referenced\\n   Which parts of the proposal were used to populate each file\\n\\n   ## Assumptions Made\\n   Consolidated list of all items marked as assumption across all files\\n   Each with: file, section, assumption text, rationale\\n\\n   ## Decisions Made (CHANGE_LOG)\\n   All generation decisions, corrections, and cross-consistency fixes\\n\\n   ## Cross-Consistency Check Results\\n   Summary of validation gate outcomes\\n\\n   ## Summary\\n   - Capabilities analyzed: N\\n   - Unique files discovered: M\\n   - Required files generated: X\\n   - Dynamic files initialized: Y\\n   - Assumptions count: Z\\n\\n2. Update _progress.json:\\n   { \\\"status\\\": \\\"COMPLETE\\\", \\\"completed_at\\\": \\\"<ISO timestamp>\\\",\\n     \\\"total\\\": len(FILE_MANIFEST), \\\"completed\\\": len(FILE_MANIFEST),\\n     \\\"items\\\": [{ \\\"name\\\": file, \\\"status\\\": \\\"COMPLETE\\\" } for each file] }\\n\\n3. Verify all files exist and are non-empty\\n\\n4. LOG: \\\"Context pack complete: {N} files generated for {M} capabilities\\\"\\n```\\n**Execution:** automated\\n\\n## Structural Conventions for Generated Files\\n\\nWhen generating any context-pack file, apply these structural conventions regardless\\nof what file it is:\\n\\n- **H1 title:** `# {Inferred Purpose}\\\\n# {Project Name} — {Project Type}`\\n- **Version header:** `**Document Version:** 1.0`\\n- **Numbered H2 sections** with domain-specific content\\n- **Tables** for structured data (tools, environments, dependencies, mappings)\\n- **Code blocks** for configuration examples, directory structures, shell commands\\n- **Footer:** `*{Project Name} {Inferred Purpose} — Globant Delivery Team*`\\n\\nWhen a `reference_context_pack` is provided and contains a matching filename,\\nuse its section structure as a skeleton — but replace ALL content with\\nproject-specific material derived from the proposal.\\n\\n## Common Rationalizations\\n\\n| Excuse | Why It Fails | Counter |\\n|--------|-------------|---------|\\n| \\\"The proposal doesn't mention tech stack, I'll pick what I know\\\" | Ungrounded tech decisions constrain the architecture phase unnecessarily | Mark recommendations as assumptions. Let the ADR phase make binding decisions. |\\n| \\\"This is greenfield, so I'll be vague\\\" | Vague context packs produce vague PRDs, vague epics, and vague code | Be specific with recommendations, but mark them as assumptions. Specificity enables the architecture phase to accept or override. |\\n| \\\"I'll just copy the reference template and change the project name\\\" | Copy-paste context packs contain irrelevant constraints from other projects | Extract structure from the reference, but generate content from THIS proposal. Every fact must trace to this project's proposal. |\\n| \\\"I don't know what this file is for, I'll skip it\\\" | A capability declared it as required — it will fail if the file is missing | Infer purpose from filename + consuming capabilities. Generate best-effort content. Flag uncertainty in the audit trail. |\\n| \\\"The proposal doesn't discuss security, I'll skip security.md\\\" | The capability declared it required — absence of discussion ≠ absence of need | Generate standard practices marked as assumptions. Flag in the audit that the proposal did not address this topic. |\\n\\n## Red Flags\\n\\nSigns that this context pack is being generated superficially:\\n\\n- All files contain identical boilerplate with only the project name changed\\n- Domain-specific concerns from the proposal don't appear in any generated file\\n- Files that discuss technology mention different/inconsistent tool sets\\n- No assumptions are marked — indicates either a perfect proposal (unlikely) or insufficient scrutiny\\n- Files were generated that no capability requires (phantom files)\\n- Files that a capability requires were NOT generated (missing files)\\n- Dynamic files contain project-specific decisions (they should be empty templates)\\n\\n## Verification Checklist\\n\\nEvery item requires **evidence**, not assertion:\\n\\n- [ ] FILE_MANIFEST matches capability YAMLs exactly — Evidence: audit trail manifest vs capability YAML cross-check\\n- [ ] Every file in FILE_MANIFEST was generated — Evidence: file existence check\\n- [ ] No file was generated outside FILE_MANIFEST — Evidence: directory listing vs manifest comparison\\n- [ ] Domain vocabulary consistent across files — Evidence: grep domain terms across all files\\n- [ ] Tech decisions aligned across related files — Evidence: tool/version cross-reference\\n- [ ] Greenfield recommendations marked as assumptions — Evidence: \\\"assumption\\\" or \\\"recommended\\\" markers present\\n- [ ] Dynamic files initialized with empty templates only — Evidence: no project decisions in dynamic files\\n- [ ] Audit trail captures all decisions — Evidence: CONTEXT-PACK-AUDIT file present with complete manifest\\n\\n## Reference Files\\n- `references/file-generation-guide.md` — Structural conventions and purpose-inference patterns\\n\\n\\n## Possible environments\\n- **uv**: Python environment management with uv virtual environments\\n- **venv**: Standard Python virtual environments\\n- **docker**: Containerized execution environments\\n- **npm/pnpm/yarn**: Node.js package management and environments\\n- **System dependencies**: Installing and configuring system-level requirements\\n- **Non-interactive setup**: Ensuring all operations run without user prompts\\n\\n## Modern Python Dependency Formats (2026)\\nPython projects in 2026 use these dependency formats (in order of preference):\\n1. **pyproject.toml** - PEP 518 standard, used by Poetry, uv, pip-tools, and modern pip\\n2. **poetry.lock** - Poetry-specific lock file (auto-generated from pyproject.toml)\\n3. **uv.lock** - uv-specific lock file (auto-generated from pyproject.toml)\\n4. **requirements.txt** - Legacy format, still supported but less common\\n\\nWhen installing dependencies, check for pyproject.toml first, then fall back to requirements.txt.\\n\\n## Environment Setup Workflow\\n\\n### Phase 1: Analysis\\n1. **Parse skill_content** to identify:\\n   - Programming language and version requirements\\n   - Package dependencies (requirements.txt, package.json, etc.)\\n   - System-level dependencies\\n   - Special configuration needs\\n2. **Validate execution_context** matches skill requirements\\n\\n### Phase 2: Environment Construction\\n\\nBased on **execution_context = \\\"native\\\"**, build the environment:\\n\\n#### For \\\"uv\\\" context (Unix/Linux/macOS):\\n```bash\\n# 1. Verify uv is installed\\nuv --version || echo \\\"ERROR: uv not found\\\"\\n\\n# 2. Create virtual environment\\ncd C:\\\\Users\\\\claudio.feitosa\\\\.coda\\\\skills\\\\creating-context-pack\\nuv venv --python 3.11\\n\\n# 3. Install dependencies non-interactively (checks modern formats first)\\nif [ -f \\\"pyproject.toml\\\" ]; then\\n    uv pip install . --no-input\\nelif [ -f \\\"requirements.txt\\\" ]; then\\n    uv pip install -r requirements.txt --no-input\\nelif [ -f \\\"requirements.txt\\\" ]; then\\n    uv pip install -r requirements.txt --no-input\\nfi\\n```\\n\\n#### For \\\"uv\\\" context (Windows PowerShell):\\n```powershell\\n# 1. Verify uv is installed\\nuv --version\\n\\n# 2. Create virtual environment\\ncd C:\\\\Users\\\\claudio.feitosa\\\\.coda\\\\skills\\\\creating-context-pack\\nuv venv --python 3.11\\n\\n# 3. Install dependencies non-interactively (checks modern formats first)\\nif (Test-Path \\\"pyproject.toml\\\") {\\n    uv pip install . --no-input\\n} elseif (Test-Path \\\"requirements.txt\\\") {\\n    uv pip install -r requirements.txt --no-input\\n} elseif (Test-Path \\\"requirements.txt\\\") {\\n    uv pip install -r requirements.txt --no-input\\n}\\n```\\n\\n#### For \\\"venv\\\" context (Unix/Linux/macOS):\\n```bash\\n# 1. Verify Python is installed\\npython3 --version || echo \\\"ERROR: Python not found\\\"\\n\\n# 2. Create virtual environment\\ncd C:\\\\Users\\\\claudio.feitosa\\\\.coda\\\\skills\\\\creating-context-pack\\npython3 -m venv .venv\\n\\n# 3. Activate and install dependencies (checks modern formats first)\\nsource .venv/bin/activate\\nif [ -f \\\"pyproject.toml\\\" ]; then\\n    pip install . --no-input --quiet\\nelif [ -f \\\"requirements.txt\\\" ]; then\\n    pip install -r requirements.txt --no-input --quiet\\nfi\\n```\\n\\n#### For \\\"venv\\\" context (Windows PowerShell):\\n```powershell\\n# 1. Verify Python is installed\\npython --version\\n\\n# 2. Create virtual environment\\ncd C:\\\\Users\\\\claudio.feitosa\\\\.coda\\\\skills\\\\creating-context-pack\\npython -m venv .venv\\n\\n# 3. Activate and install dependencies (checks modern formats first)\\n.venv\\\\Scripts\\\\Activate.ps1\\nif (Test-Path \\\"pyproject.toml\\\") {\\n    pip install . --no-input --quiet\\n} elseif (Test-Path \\\"requirements.txt\\\") {\\n    pip install -r requirements.txt --no-input --quiet\\n}\\n```\\n\\n#### For \\\"docker\\\" context:\\n```bash\\n# 1. Verify Docker is installed and running\\ndocker --version && docker ps || echo \\\"ERROR: Docker not available\\\"\\n\\n# 2. Build image (if Dockerfile exists) or use base image\\ncd C:\\\\Users\\\\claudio.feitosa\\\\.coda\\\\skills\\\\creating-context-pack\\nif [ -f \\\"Dockerfile\\\" ]; then\\n    docker build -t creating-context-pack-env . --quiet\\nelse\\n    docker pull python:3.11-slim --quiet\\nfi\\n```\\n\\n#### For \\\"npm\\\" context:\\n```bash\\n# 1. Check for Node.js version requirement in package.json and use nvm if available\\ncd C:\\\\Users\\\\claudio.feitosa\\\\.coda\\\\skills\\\\creating-context-pack\\nif [ -f \\\"package.json\\\" ] && command -v nvm &> /dev/null; then\\n    source ~/.nvm/nvm.sh || source ~/.config/nvm/nvm.sh || true\\n    REQUIRED_NODE=$(node -pe \\\"try { require('./package.json').engines?.node || '' } catch(e) { '' }\\\")\\n    if [ ! -z \\\"$REQUIRED_NODE\\\" ]; then\\n        nvm install \\\"$REQUIRED_NODE\\\" --silent\\n        nvm use \\\"$REQUIRED_NODE\\\" --silent\\n    fi\\nfi\\n\\n# 2. Verify Node.js and package manager are available\\nnode --version && npm --version || echo \\\"ERROR: Node.js not found\\\"\\n\\n# 3. Install dependencies non-interactively\\nnpm install --silent --no-progress --yes\\n\\n# 4. Verify package.json scripts are available\\ncat package.json | grep '\\\"scripts\\\"' || echo \\\"WARNING: No scripts defined\\\"\\n```\\n\\n### Phase 3: Validation (Dry Run)\\n\\nPerform non-destructive tests to verify the environment:\\n\\n1. **Basic validation:**\\n   - For Python: Run `python --version` in the environment\\n   - For Node: Run `node --version` and verify modules load\\n   - For Docker: Run `docker run --rm <image> <version-command>`\\n\\n2. **Dependency check:**\\n   - List installed packages: `pip list`, `npm list --depth=0`, etc.\\n   - Verify critical dependencies are present\\n\\n3. **Simple execution test:**\\n   - Run a minimal test command (e.g., `python -c \\\"import sys; print(sys.version)\\\"`)\\n   - DO NOT execute the actual skill scripts yet\\n\\n4. **Safety checks:**\\n   - Verify no network access required for basic operation (if isolated environment)\\n   - Check file permissions in C:\\\\Users\\\\claudio.feitosa\\\\.coda\\\\skills\\\\creating-context-pack\\n   - Ensure environment is properly isolated (if not native context)\\n\\n### Phase 4: Execution Instructions\\n\\nAfter successful validation, provide:\\n\\n1. **Activation command** (for virtual environments):\\n   ```bash\\n   # How to activate the environment\\n   ```\\n\\n2. **Execution command** for running the skill scripts:\\n   ```bash\\n   # How to run the main skill script\\n   ```\\n\\n3. **Deactivation/cleanup** (if applicable):\\n   ```bash\\n   # How to exit the environment\\n   ```\\n\\n## Critical Requirements\\n\\n### ⚠️ NON-INTERACTIVE OPERATION\\n\\nALL commands MUST run non-interactively:\\n\\n- Use flags: `--yes`, `-y`, `--no-input`, `--silent`, `--quiet`, `--assume-yes`\\n- Set environment variables: `CI=true`, `DEBIAN_FRONTEND=noninteractive`, `PIP_NO_INPUT=1`\\n- Pipe defaults: `echo \\\"yes\\\" | command` for unavoidable prompts\\n- Pre-configure: Use config files instead of interactive setup\\n\\n**Common non-interactive patterns:**\\n```bash\\n# Package managers\\npip install -r requirements.txt --no-input\\nnpm install --yes\\npnpm install --no-optional\\napt-get install -y package-name\\n\\n# Python environment\\nuv venv --python 3.11  # No prompts\\npython -m venv .venv   # No prompts\\n\\n# Docker\\ndocker build -t name . --quiet\\ndocker run --rm image  # Use --rm for cleanup\\n```\\n\\n### ⚠️ TIMEOUT MANAGEMENT\\n\\nAdjust bash command timeouts for long-running operations:\\n\\n- Package installations: 300000-600000ms (5-10 minutes)\\n- Docker builds: 600000ms (10 minutes)\\n- Dependency resolution: 180000-300000ms (3-5 minutes)\\n\\n**Example:**\\n```python\\nbash(command=\\\"uv pip install -r requirements.txt\\\", timeout=300000)\\n```\\n\\n### ⚠️ ERROR HANDLING\\n\\nIf environment setup fails:\\n\\n1. Capture the exact error message\\n2. Identify the failing command\\n3. Report to user with:\\n   - What failed\\n   - Why it failed\\n   - How to fix it (installation instructions, missing dependencies, etc.)\\n4. DO NOT proceed to validation if setup failed\\n\\n## Platform-Specific Considerations\\n\\n- Activation scripts: Use appropriate syntax (`source` for Unix, `Scripts\\\\` for Windows)\\n- Path separators: Use forward slashes on Unix, backslashes on Windows\\n- Shell compatibility: Assume bash/zsh on Unix, PowerShell on Windows\\n- Package managers: Verify availability (apt for Ubuntu, brew for macOS, chocolatey for Windows)\\n\\n## Remember: for running the previous skill instructions\\n- NEVER run interactive commands - always use non-interactive flags\\n\\nUse the previous instructions for executing the user scripts following the rules and guidelines provided.\\n\"}}\n74: {\"event\": \"tool_call\", \"tool\": \"think\", \"args\": {\"thought\": \"Now I need to analyze the inputs for context-pack generation. Based on the skill instructions and the current situation:\\n\\n1. I have a project brief (PRD) as the primary input\\n2. The skill expects capability YAML files to determine what files to generate\\n3. I need to check if there are capability files in the project\\n4. The skill should create context pack files based on capability requirements\\n\\nLet me check what capability files exist and then execute the context pack creation process.\\n\\nKey parameters needed:\\n- proposal_path: C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\artifacts\\\\inputs\\\\documentation\\\\project-brief_1783100063082-dq1jh13x.md\\n- context_pack_path: C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\context-pack \\n- capabilities_path: Need to find where capability YAMLs are located\\n\\nI should first look for capability files, then run the context pack creation process.\"}}\n75: {\"event\": \"intermediate_response\", \"content\": \"\\nLet me search for capability YAML files in the project structure:\\n\"}\n76: {\"event\": \"tool_call\", \"tool\": \"bash\", \"args\": {\"command\": \"findstr /s /i \\\"capability.*yaml\\\" C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\*.*\"}}\n77: {\"event\": \"tool_result\", \"tool\": \"bash\", \"is_error\": false, \"result\": {\"status\": \"success\", \"stdout\": \"C:\\\\QAx\\\\002\\\\workflow\\\\instances\\\\context-pack\\\\sessions\\\\a305a802-3931-4be3-81fa-355fb8ed3c2b\\\\agent-run\\\\analyze-context-pack-inputs__1783100070734-87n83z6n.log:{\\\"event\\\": \\\"intermediate_response\\\", \\\"content\\\": \\\"\\\\nLet me check if there are any capability YAML files or definitions that m